ALLELES, RECOMBINATION & LINKAGE
Investigate Activity:
1. Define genetic loci and alleles.
The genetic loci is the exact location of a gene in the chromosome.
Alleles are different variants of the same gene.
2. Critically explain what alleles are, and how they are expressed.
Phenotypes, or the outward appearance of an organism, are dependent on alleles. These alleles
can either be dominant or recessive. A heterozygous organism that carries one recessive and
one dominant allele at a specific locus will exhibit the dominant phenotype at that locus.
3. Critically explain how alleles segregate during mitosis and meiosis.
Gametes are divided randomly into alleles derived from one parent: During gamete formation,
each allele of a parent is divided evenly among the gametes, so that half of each allele carries by
itself.
Consolidate Activity: Finding Genes and linkages with Ensembl Genome
Browsers
Ensembl genome browser (EGB) provides access to organised information or annotated data from
the analysis of biological data. Genome browsers and their underlying databases act as single entry
points to data from multiple projects and genomic analyses, such as genes and proteins, sequence
variation, comparative genomics and motifs involved in gene regulation.
Ensembl provides a genome browser that acts as a single point of access to annotated genomes for
mainly vertebrate species, including human, mouse, rat, zebrafish, panda, and takifugu. Information
such as gene sequence, splice variants and further annotation can be retrieved at the genome, gene
and protein level.
